The Varieties of Turkish Nationalism
Step 2: Latent Class Analyses

This RMarkdown file uses Latent Class Analysis (LCA) to identify the varieties of nationalism in Turkey.

1 Latent Class Model Selection

1.1 Successive LCA Models Using poLCA Package

Let us first fit successive LCA models, ranging from 1 class to 10 classes.

lca.fits.baseline <- list()
set.seed(11235)
for (loopfr in 1:10) {
  lcafits <- poLCA(
    cbind(
      natident1,
      natident2,
      natpride1,
      natpride2,
      natmembr1,
      natmembr2,
      natmembr3,
      natmembr4,
      nathubrs1,
      nathubrs2,
      nathubrs3,
      nathubrs4,
      natcultr1,
      natcultr2
    ) ~ 1,
    nclass = loopfr,
    nrep = 30,
    maxiter = 5000,
    data = df,
    verbose = F
  )
  lca.fits.baseline[[loopfr]] <- lcafits
}
rm(loopfr, lcafits) # clean-up

1.1.1 Fit Statistics

# collect fit statistics
lca.fits.fitstats <- 
  as.data.frame(matrix(NA, nrow = 10, ncol = 5))

for (loopfr in 1:10) {
  model <- lca.fits.baseline[[loopfr]]
  lca.fits.fitstats[loopfr, 1] <- loopfr
  lca.fits.fitstats[loopfr, 2] <- model$bic # BIC
  lca.fits.fitstats[loopfr, 3] <- model$aic # AIC
  lca.fits.fitstats[loopfr, 4] <- model$llik # Log-Likelihood
  lca.fits.fitstats[loopfr, 5] <- model$Gsq # Likelihood / Deviance
}
rm(model, loopfr) # clean-up

# pretty names
lca.fits.fitstats <- lca.fits.fitstats |>
  rename(N = V1,
         BIC = V2,
         AIC = V3,
         LLL = V4,
         GSQ = V5)

# plot the resultant statistics
lca.fits.fitstats |>
  pivot_longer(cols = !N, names_to = "Statistics", values_to = "Values") |>
  ggplot(aes(x = factor(N),
             y = Values)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line(size = .25, group = 1, linetype = "dashed") +
  labs(x = "The Number of Classes",
       y = "Fit Statistics") +
  theme_ipsum_rc() +
  facet_wrap(~ Statistics, nrow = 2, scales = "free_y")

The BIC clearly elbows at N = 4, which is in line with the previous literature. Lets do the same analyses with glca. This package will allow us to calculate \(G^2\) statistics along with bootstrap tests to validate whether N = 4 is the right choice.

1.2 Successive LCA Models Using gLCA Package

lca.fits.validate <- list()
set.seed(11235)
for (loopfr in 2:10) {
  glcafits <- glca(
    item(
      natident1,
      natident2,
      natpride1,
      natpride2,
      natmembr1,
      natmembr2,
      natmembr3,
      natmembr4,
      nathubrs1,
      nathubrs2,
      nathubrs3,
      nathubrs4,
      natcultr1,
      natcultr2
    ) ~ 1,
    nclass = loopfr,
    n.init = 30,
    maxiter = 5000,
    data = df,
    verbose = F
  )
  lca.fits.validate[[loopfr]] <- glcafits
}
rm(loopfr, glcafits) # clean-up

1.2.1 Fit Statistics

set.seed(11235)
lca.fits.validfit <- gofglca(
  lca.fits.validate[[2]],
  lca.fits.validate[[3]],
  lca.fits.validate[[4]],
  lca.fits.validate[[5]],
  lca.fits.validate[[6]],
  lca.fits.validate[[7]], 
  lca.fits.validate[[8]], 
  lca.fits.validate[[9]], 
  lca.fits.validate[[10]], test = "boot")

1.3 Model with 4 Classes

OK, we can now fit the model with N = 4 and several covariates. Some of the covariates (particularly party and relig) have sparse cells in the four-class solution, so we merge some of the categorical cells to achieve model convergence.

# some brushes
df <- df |>
  mutate(
    party.bags = recode(
      party,
      "none" = "none",
      "cumhur" = "cumhur",
      "millet" = "millet",
      "emek" = "other",
      "other" = "other"
    ),
    relig.bags = ifelse(relig == "muslim", 0, 1)
  )

# model fit
set.seed(11234)
lca.data.4classes <- poLCA(
  cbind(
    natident1,
    natident2,
    natpride1,
    natpride2,
    natmembr1,
    natmembr2,
    natmembr3,
    natmembr4,
    nathubrs1,
    nathubrs2,
    nathubrs3,
    nathubrs4,
    natcultr1,
    natcultr2
  ) ~
    gender + age + ethnic + educ + relig.bags + religiosity + lifestyle + 
    party.bags + ideology + polint + polinfo,
  nclass = 4,
  probs.start = lca.fits.baseline[[4]]$probs.start,
  nrep = 1,
  maxiter = 5000,
  data = df,
  verbose = F
)

# no need for old brushes
df <- df |> dplyr::select(-c(relig.bags, party.bags))

2 Latent Class Model Metrics

2.1 Visualizing Classes

Lets visualize the composition of response patterns across four classes. Depending on the seed used, the ordering of the classes might change (see the seed used in the Latent Class fits above for the full replication of the following code).

## visualize the item-response probabilities

broom::tidy(lca.data.4classes) |>
  group_by(variable, class) |>
  mutate(class = factor(
    class,
    levels = c(4, 2, 1, 3),
    labels = c("Ardent",
               "Creedal",
               "Disengaged",
               "Moderate")
  )) |>
  mutate(
    group = ifelse(
      variable %in% c("natident1",
                      "natident2"),
      "Identification",
      ifelse(
        variable %in% c("natpride1",
                        "natpride2"),
        "Pride",
        ifelse(
          variable %in% c("natcultr1",
                          "natcultr2"),
          "Culture",
          ifelse(
            variable %in% c(
              "natmembr1",
              "natmembr2",
              "natmembr3",
              "natmembr4"
            ),
            "Membership Criteria",
            "Hubris"
          )
        )
      )
    )) |>
      mutate(group = factor(
        group,
        levels = c(
          "Identification",
          "Pride",
          "Membership Criteria",
          "Hubris",
          "Culture"
        )
      )) |>
      ggplot(aes(
        x = variable,
        y = estimate,
        fill = factor(
          outcome,
          levels = c("1", "2", "3", "4", "5"),
          labels = c(
            "Strongly Disagree",
            "Disagree",
            "Neither Agree Nor Disagree",
            "Agree",
            "Strongly Agree"
          )
        )
      )) +
      geom_bar(
        stat = "identity",
        position = "stack",
        color = "black"
      ) +
      facet_grid(class ~ group, scale = "free_x", space = "free") +
      theme_ipsum_rc(grid = F) +
      theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 0.75)) +
      theme(legend.position = "right") +
      labs(x = "Variables", y = "Estimated Item Values", fill = "Response") +
      scale_fill_brewer(type = "seq", palette = "RdBu")

2.2 Group Differences

In what follows, we present the differences among nationalist classes in terms of several demographics.

df <- df |>
  mutate(class = lca.data.4classes$predclass) |>
  mutate(class = factor(
    class,
    levels = c(4, 2, 1, 3),
    labels = c("Ardent",
               "Creedal",
               "Disengaged",
               "Moderate")
  ))
